snippet.textDisplay: I was the same as Charlie I started but didn’t keep playing idk why , souls game souls likes are the easiest to backlog even though you know if you keep playing it’ll the only game you’ll play for like 100 hours or so, i really liked the game but I also thought there’s a lot of bad things in it or bad mechanics, I think weapon durability is cheap , only really wears off during a boss battle and a lot of these bosses are agressive and tighter areas and not that many emergency repairs available , I also think boss fights that have multiple status effects is an absolute No no. the black rabbit brotherhood 2nd fight is so bad imo it’s not an ounce of satisfaction or much skill to it the first fight I beat first try , the second fight it took me 26 times the aggro is so inconsistent the fight is RNG for wether you’ll die 20 times or only 2 times , the moves aren’t hard to perfect block at all but it’s hard when you got one pulling you into him while one then dashes across the arena to hit you bc it’s a non block able move that you’re camera loses lock on for when you’re pulled in and then the eldest later in the fight when it should’ve been a 1 on 1 rematch later in the area bc the area is so short , I feel a lot of the two phase bosses are not consistent one phase will be way better than the other like king of puppets , first phase is meh the 2nd phase is amazing, laxasia is great first phase , can’t tell wtf she’s gonna do in the 2nd phase bc of nonstop particle effects and lack of animation as she darts around the arena. and then minus was underwhelming with a okay first phase and a not so good 2nd phase. I love how satisfying most of the game is it’s world it’s art design it’s score it’s story it’s characters and combat when it’s done right. I also feel that it’s inconsistent that one build is vastly superior than the others. This game is immensely more artificially difficult if you’re a strength build. any weapon that strikes two hands simply is way to slow , and the fast weapons are way too fast with the damage they deal and stamina it keeps. Even with weapon customization you it’s not worth putting a motivity weapon on a advance handle bc I lose over a 100 damage for a weapon that still is considerably slower and takes way more stamina even in the handle so might as well just be tech or advance. and it’s confusing that cranks are so rare despite this pretty lenient exploration of the weapons. it’s definitely the best souls like but I don’t feel it’s a masterpiece I think it’s an amazing game , it works well except for heavy pop in but it’s such a creative , fun game that’s addictive. Even in gank only the brotherhood made me not care to continue for a bit but I wanted and needed to beat everyone else and to think this is this developers FIRST real game?! That’s where you get really excited for what’s next wether it’s another souls like or anything else I’m gonna be ready for what it is

Honorable Mentions: Sekiro and Bloodborne

For me personally, DS3 was always better than elden ring. Not mechanically or whateever else, just personally. Elden ring is an amazing game and deserves the Game of the Year award as well as many peoples personal #1 souls game. However I don't think anything can beat how I felt after playing my first souls-like, being DS3. I've since beaten it countless times. Elden Ring was still a good challenge but for me, its only slighly less fun, not even worse. I beat it 4 times and let it go for a bit during my 5th playthough, because of time. Lies of P, however, gave me the same feeling as my first ever souls-like(DS3) and I fell in love immediately. I had all of this dark souls like experience with ds3, ds2, ds1 and elden ring, and now I get to be thrust in an entirely different theme of souls-like that was eternally captivating for me. I enjoyed every encounter(minus the fat clown sequence with the 3 spinning flame ball hurlers and the 4 flamethrowers. It was a skill issue).  There's simplicity, and complexity. Humanity, and something worse so the former can prevail. The mechanics are the smoothest to learn out of any souls-like, in my experience.  I am accounting for my experience in other games regarding the 'fluidity' of learning the mechanics, it's just a really smooth engine. Despite it lacking in classes, they made up for it by balancing all of the encounters with the environments, item spawns, drop rates, gold coin fruit, shop expansions, quartz, legion calibers, etc. Truly a souls-like in a different universe that follows its own rules of fiction instead of that of another. 

Sekiro and Bloodborne are honourable mentions purely based off of my lack of experience in those games currently. They are contenders for my top 3 after what I have seen. Feel free to reply with your rankings or why you may agree/disagree with mine! Keep it civil please.

snippet.textDisplay: Loved this game. I also loved the quality of life changes for example you can grab your ergo at a boss entrance instead of being forced to kill the boss. It also has markers pointing which NPC's have new quest related dialogue unlike in fromsoft where NPC's might be in bum fuck nowhere. I also loved the handle system, if you like how a weapon looks, but hate it's attack pattern, you can change it to any other previously aquired weapon and the stats will be the same. Only thing i kinda disliked was how easy the last two bosses were expect Laxasia. Also two things people don't talk about enough, the optimization is fucking amazing, i'm getting 100+fps on my RTX 2060 laptop on high settings and the game uses UE4, but looks better than a lot of UE5 modern games. Second thing i'd like to talk about is the voice actors, gotta give some credit especially King of Riddles, Simon and Gepetto.
